english:
  title: 'In Praise of the Layman of No-Ability: Preface and Eulogy'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Lord of Miryangcheon, Park Gong, spoke to me saying: "The teacher of the Former King, the National Master Taego, bestowed upon Seongryang the name 'No-Ability.' Among those who held the brush in the Former Dynasty, only you remain. I am fortunate to ask you for a word that might illuminate its meaning."

    I reflected thus: When Gong served at Songnung, he was greatly beloved. Even after the abdication to Gangdo, he never strayed a step from the royal side, and all revered his loyalty. Recognized by Kongmin Wang, he became a minister of the inner court, known for his caution and care. The present sovereign has elevated him to the Central Secretariat, yet he takes no joy in honor or name. He holds only the temple rites and Buddhist affairs as his sacred charge. For more than a decade he continues unwavering, his heart still undiminished. Truly, his loyalty has reached its apex.

    For one to be human, loyalty and righteousness alone suffice. Though his deeds astonish the world and startle the common mind, without these virtues, nothing is worthy of praise. Looking upon Gong's life: in serving his sovereign, he perfected his devotion; in serving Buddha, he perfected his way. Though he bears the name No-Ability, I cannot accept it as true. Yet the Buddhist dharma is emptiness and stillness. Within that emptiness and stillness dwell neither common folk nor sages, neither form nor name. How then could ability or its object exist? Where ability and object remain, the supreme way has not been reached. Taego's hopes for Gong ran very deep. I myself am no master of such matters. With only what little I have heard, I offer this humble praise:

    From the Original Teacher, he received benevolence;
    From the First Ancestor, he received grace.
    In emptiness and stillness, others clung like tumors and warts.
    Yet Gong alone remained untouched—
    And thus the wind stirred with each step he took.

    Who could truly know this man? Only Taego, that one.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Taego (太古): A renowned Zen master and Gong''s spiritual teacher who bestowed the dharma name ''No-Ability'' (無能)'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'emptiness and stillness' (空寂) referenced reflects core Buddhist philosophy—the ultimate truth transcends all dualities and conceptual categories
  - key: ''
    value: The image of 'wind stirring with each step' suggests spiritual presence and virtue emanating naturally, without deliberate effort
